INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'eda7f5bb-474b-4231-a850-378501a6ce03',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$BigQuery Partitioning & Clustering — Cut Costs with Partition Pruning$escape$,
  $escape$BigQuery charges by bytes scanned, so partition pruning is your first line of defense. When you filter on a partitioned column, BigQuery skips entire partition files — but only if your WHERE clause directly references that column without wrapping it in a function. `WHERE DATE(event_timestamp) = '2024-01-01'` disables pruning; `WHERE event_timestamp BETWEEN '2024-01-01' AND '2024-01-02'` enables it.

For time-series tables, prefer `TIMESTAMP`-based partitioning over `DATE` ingestion time (`_PARTITIONTIME`) — it gives you explicit control and works with `partition_expiration_days` to auto-expire stale data. Layer clustering on top with up to 4 columns ordered by query filter frequency: `CLUSTER BY user_id, event_type` means filters on `user_id` alone still benefit, but `event_type` alone does not.

Use `INFORMATION_SCHEMA.PARTITIONS` to audit partition sizes and catch skew early. A single hot partition (e.g., a `NULL` catch-all) can silently destroy query performance. Set `require_partition_filter = TRUE` on large tables to enforce discipline across the team.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Partition pruning: good vs bad
-- BAD: function wrapping disables pruning
SELECT * FROM `project.dataset.events`
WHERE DATE(event_timestamp) = '2024-01-15';

-- GOOD: direct range filter enables pruning
SELECT * FROM `project.dataset.events`
WHERE event_timestamp >= '2024-01-15 00:00:00 UTC'
  AND event_timestamp <  '2024-01-16 00:00:00 UTC';

-- Inspect partition sizes for skew
SELECT partition_id, total_rows, total_logical_bytes
FROM `project.dataset.INFORMATION_SCHEMA.PARTITIONS`
ORDER BY total_logical_bytes DESC
LIMIT 10;$escape$,
