INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e471f323-a0fe-4271-b2a2-469447456bb3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$BigQuery Semi-Structured Data — JSON Type, Nested STRUCTs, and Schema Evolution Without the Pain$escape$,
  $escape$BigQuery's native JSON type (GA since 2023) stores payloads in a binary-encoded format — unlike STRING columns with JSON text, JSON_VALUE() and JSON_QUERY() operate on pre-parsed structure, avoiding repeated deserialization overhead at query time.

For nested data, BigQuery uses STRUCT and ARRAY types natively. When loading Parquet, group fields map to STRUCT and repeated fields map to ARRAY<T> automatically — no schema hinting required. Use bq load --autodetect or define the schema explicitly to preserve nesting depth across ingestion.

Schema evolution on existing tables uses ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS. You cannot surgically add subfields inside an existing STRUCT — instead, add a new top-level nullable column or use CREATE TABLE AS SELECT with EXCEPT() to reshape. Nullable top-level additions are metadata-only operations with no data rewrite.

When querying, JSON_VALUE() returns STRING scalars, JSON_QUERY() returns a JSON subobject, and JSON_VALUE_ARRAY() extracts string arrays cleanly. Combine UNNEST() with ARRAY<STRUCT<>> columns to explode repeated records into flat rows — BigQuery's optimizer pushes predicates into the UNNEST, so filter before unnesting to minimize scanned bytes.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Extract from native JSON type + unnest repeated STRUCT<>
SELECT
  e.event_id,
  JSON_VALUE(e.payload, '$.user_id')        AS user_id,
  JSON_VALUE(e.payload, '$.action')         AS action,
  attr.key,
  attr.value
FROM `project.dataset.events` e,
  UNNEST(e.attributes) AS attr  -- ARRAY<STRUCT<key STRING, value STRING>>
WHERE DATE(e.created_at) = CURRENT_DATE()
  AND JSON_VALUE(e.payload, '$.action') = 'purchase'
  AND attr.key = 'sku';$escape$,
  $escape$sql$escape$,
